          <ab><pb n="1v"/><lb n="01"/>dr̥ṣṭaṁ</ab>
          <!-- 
SK treat dr̥ṣṭaṁ as part of l1, but it is definitely a separate block, being a little lower than l1 and starting right at the edge of the plate, before the margin of the subsequent lines. L1 itself starts with an indent of about 1 character. Also, though this may be an artefact of the rubbing, it seems pretty certain that dr̥ṣṭaṁ was engraved after the text of l2 was already in place. The subscript ṭ intersects the vowel of śrī in l2, and - in the inked rubbing - the white line of the ṭ has a thin black edge at this intersection. This edge is too thin to assume that the ī mātrā was inscribed after the ṭ was in place, and its line was interrupted at the intersection point then continued on; but it seems perfectly plausible that the edge is a kerf mark (or whatever the proper term is) raised by the engraver's tool when inscribing the ṭ after the ī. 
-->
          <p><lb n="1"/>jitam bhagavatā<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> svasti vainyāpura-sthānā<supplied reason="omitted">d</supplied></p>
          <p>guptānām ādi-rājo mahārā<lb break="no" n="2"/>ja-śrī-ghaṭotkacas tat-putro mahārāja-śrī-candraguptas tasya putras tat-pā<!-- 
L2. Not noted by SK, mahā may be a correction, perhaps from hamā. 
--><!-- 
L2. SK print the sta of putras tat as supplied (they literally print "पुत्र Ì(स्त*]त्पा", sic). This seems to be some sort of weird typo; sta is clear. 
--><lb break="no" n="3"/>da-parigr̥hī<space type="binding-hole"/>to licchavi-dauhitro mahādevyā<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> kumāradevyām utpann<choice>
              <sic>a</sic>
              <corr>o</corr>
            </choice><!-- 
L3. SK read licchavī and specifically note this as an instance of mixing up i and ī marks. In the rubbing the mark could very well pass for short i; actually, the one in dauhitro looks more like ī. So why not give the engraver the benefit of doubt? 
--><!-- 
L3. SK read utpanna as in compound, but I think the intent must have been utpanno. Compare #IN00164:4. 
--><lb n="4"/>mahārāja-śrī-samudraguptas tasya putras tat-pādānu<unclear>ddh</unclear>yāto nyāyāgat<choice>
              <sic>a</sic>
              <corr>ā</corr>
            </choice>neka<!-- 
L4. SK read °anudhyāto here (but °anuddhyātā in l10). The topmost part of the ligature cannot be dh, so I take it as a badly formed d (looking like v); between this part and the subscript y there is a faint curve that seems to be the left-hand side of dh. 
--><lb break="no" n="5"/>-go-hiraṇya-koṭi-sahasra-pradas sarvva-rājocchet<supplied reason="omitted">t</supplied>ā p<choice>
              <sic>ri</sic>
              <corr>r̥</corr>
            </choice>thivyām apratiratha<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><!-- 
L5. saha may be a correction, or just not very nicely formed. The sa is awkward; the ha may have been first inscribed as another sa. 
--><!-- 
L5. SK print pr̥thivyām (certainly, as their edition is in Devanagari), but the plate has prithivyām. 
--><pb n="2r"/><!-- 
From the beginning of 2recto, the text seems to be in a different hand. Maybe we should mark up the hand change in proper XML. The characters in this second hand are neater and slightly larger. The most conspicuous mark of the hand change is the form of the subscript y, which is practically a circle here, very much like (or completely identical to?) the form used in the Masod plates, IN00184. The first hand used the regular form of subscript y. Also, the hand2 uses a distinctly southern ja, without a box head, but with a wavy top line and a wavy left vertical. (The same outline appears in ṅ in l8.) ṇa is probably also different: in hand1 (only 1 specimen on 1verso, not very clear and in ligature) it seems to be a regular vākāṭaka ṇ with a boxhead, very similar to no; in hand2 ṇa has no boxhead, only a pair of wings at the top. In hand2, ī seems always to be marked with a double circle (śrī at the end of l6 may in fact be śri, but part is rubbed off and śrī is not impossible); in hand1, neither i nor ī are closed into a circle (both being open on the left), but i is just a curve, while ī is a spiral. In hand2, ā mātrās are attached to the top of most consonants; in hand1 this happens occasionally but the general rule seems that ā mātrās are on the right-hand side. 
--><lb n="6"/>parama-bhāgavato m<surplus>m</surplus>ahādevyā<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> dattadevyām utpanno m<surplus>m</surplus>ahārājādhirāja-śr<unclear>ī</unclear>-
<lb n="7"/>candraguptas tasya duhitā dhāraṇa-sagotrā nāga-kulotpannāyā<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> ku<sic>mā</sic>ranāg<choice>
              <sic>a</sic>
              <corr>ā</corr>
            </choice><!-- 
L7. SK print candraguptasya, but the plate has candraguptas tasya (and so does IN00164:7). 
--><!-- 
L7. As SK point out, Prabhāvatīguptā's mother ought to be Kuberanāgā, not Kumāranāgā. 
--><lb break="no" n="8"/>-d<unclear>e</unclear>vyām utpannā <space type="binding-hole"/> ubhaya-kulālaṅkāra-bhūtā vākāṭakānām mahārāja-śrī<!-- 
L8. SK read davyām, emending to devyām. I think the e mātrā is faintly visible. 
