          <p>yūyam asmābhir iha cāmutra ca sva-puṇyāpyāyanā<unclear>r</unclear>ttha<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied><!-- 
L13. SK print °ārtthaṁ as clear. This is the very edge of the plate, and SK's rubbing seems to end a hair's breadth before the edge, but there is almost certainly no anusvāra, and only a faint trace of what may be a superscript r. 
--><lb n="14"/>kāśyapa-sagotra-vājasaney<choice>
              <unclear>i</unclear>
              <unclear>a</unclear>
            </choice>-m<sic>a</sic>ddhyandina<unclear>|</unclear> bhaṭy<unclear>ā</unclear>ryy<unclear>ā</unclear>-svāmikāryya<!-- 
L14. SK print kaśyapa (also writing about Kaśyapa gotra in their commentary, p141). kā is clear in the rubbing. 
--><!-- 
L14. SK print vājasaneya (also in their commentary). I'm fairly certain the plate actually has vājasaneyi, though the i mātrā is faint and squashed on acount of smā hanging down from above. 
--><!-- 
L14. Where I read an unclear daṇḍa, SK read (and delete) a visarga. It is not damaged at all, consisting very clearly of two very short horizontal dashes. I think a visarga is unlikely at this point (especially since there have so far been no clear visargas in the inscription even where expected), and the mark is probably punctuation, perhaps in a function sort of like a colon, to imply that the gotra etc specifications apply to all the following names. 
--><!-- 
L14. SK read bhaṭṭyāryya, emending to bhaṭṭāryya (which is the name they mention in their commentary). I think bhaṭṭy-āryya would be perfectly acceptable, but the plate actually has bhaṭyāryyā (the first ā mātrā is all but invisible, but I assume it is there since it's expected and SK read it; the second is also unclear and SK do not read it, but it is more discernible than the first and matches the āryyās in the following line). Nonetheless, the intent was probably bhaṭṭy-āryya. 
--><lb break="no" n="15"/>-govyāryyā-śaṅkarāryyā-dharāryyāya<unclear>|</unclear> udaka-pūrvvam atisr̥ṣṭā<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><!-- 
L15. SK read govyāryya-śaṅkarāryya; the unexpected ā endings of both are clear in the rubbing. 
--><!-- 
L15. SK read dharāryyāyaḥ, deleting the visarga. I think once again that this is a punctuation mark (though it is not identical to the one in l14, the dashes being even shorter and closer together), marking the end of the list. 
--><!-- 
L15. SK emend atisr̥ṣṭā to atisr̥ṣṭa, which doesn't seem to make sense. I believe the intent must have been atisr̥ṣṭāḥ, which is consistent with the lack of visargas throughout the text so far, and agrees grammatically with yūyam - even though addressing people as chattel does seem sort of surprising. 
--></p>
          <p><pb n="3r"/><!-- 
L16. At 3 recto the hand changes back to the first one or at any rate one very much like the first one. 
--><lb n="16"/>Ucitā<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied>ś cāsya pūrvva-rājānumatā<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied>ś <choice>
              <sic>cātura<unclear>tt</unclear>a</sic>
              <corr>cāturvvaidya</corr>
            </choice>-grāma-maryyādā śarkkara<!-- 
L16. SK read °anumatāścāturatra, emending to °anumatācaturatra, at least in their edition. The text cited in their commentary (p141) is °anumatāś cātur atra, so they seem to understand "atra"; I have no idea how they construe catur or cātur - is this supposed to mean four boundaries? While "atra grāma-maryyādā" makes some sense, the plate definitely doesn't have tra. The character appars to be tta or possibly nta (though n has, I believe, been always looped so far, and tta in l18 doesn't look identical: this one uses the symmetrical (older?) subscript t, while elsewhere it's an angled projection from the descender). So most probably this is just a weird error for cāturvvaidya, and perhaps the engraver didn't even know or care what character he was producing. Then the text gets seriously jumbled: the expected continuation, parihārān, comes in l18 below (and it is preceded, rather than followed by tad yathā). Perhaps the plates are copies of an earlier set, which had the boundaries added to the bottom of one plate that originally ended at maryyādā? 
--><!-- 
L16. In addition to the hand change, we now begin to get jumbled-up text like in the Masod plate. 
--><lb break="no" n="17"/>-grā<choice>
              <sic>p</sic>
              <corr>m</corr>
            </choice>asya pūrvvato vaṭapadrakasya dakṣiṇato haredrakāyā<choice>
