              <sic>li</sic>
              <corr>l̥</corr>
            </choice>ptopak<choice>
              <sic>li</sic>
              <corr>l̥</corr>
            </choice>pta<space/> ācandrāditya-kālīyaḥ putra-pautrānugāmī<!-- 
L22. There is a mark in the space after klipta, not read by SK. It is probably not a visarga; it seems to be a dot a bit above baseline, and another dot lower and to the right of the first one. Either or both may be random marks on the plate. 
--><lb n="23"/>bhuñjatā<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> na ke<space type="binding-hole"/><choice>
              <sic>ṇ</sic>
              <corr>n</corr>
            </choice>aci<supplied reason="omitted">d</supplied> vyāghātayitavyaḥ sarvva-kkr<choice>
              <sic>a</sic>
              <corr>i</corr>
            </choice>yābhis saṁrakṣita<!-- 
L23. SK read keṇacid, but the d is not there in the plate. 
--><!-- 
L23. As SK observe, the usual (or perhaps universal?) reading instead of vyāghātayitavyaḥ is vyāghātaḥ karttavyaḥ, which according to SK is also "the correct one". To me vyāghātayitavyaḥ looks much better grammatically; this may have been a semi-conscious improvement on the standard text by a literate drafter. 
--><lb break="no" n="24"/>vya<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> paripālayitavyaś ca| yaś cāsmac-chāsanam agaṇayamāna<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> svalp<unclear>ā</unclear><!-- 
L24. SK print paripāyitavyaś ca, but they do not emend it, so they must have read the correct paripālayitavyaś ca, and this is a typo in their edition. 
--><!-- 
L24. The punctuation mark is indistinguishable from a visarga. SK describe it as "a short horizontal stroke above and a short vertical stroke below", which is literally true, but probably of no consequence; it must have been mean to be two dots. 
