--><pb n="4r"/><lb n="26"/><surplus>r</surplus>v<surplus>v</surplus>editasya sa-daṇḍaṁ nigrahaṁ kariṣyāma<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><!-- 
L26. SK read vveditasya, emending to rvveditasya. The superscript r is in fact quite clear, and the e mātrā is attached to its top, not to the boxhead. However, SK do not mention the fact that the reading does not splice well with the end of plate 3. I emend to āveditasya to get a seamless transition, but my suspicion is that plate 3 is a replacement or a forgery. veditasya and āveditasya both occur in this context in cognate plates, though I think āveditasya is much more common. But the original plate3 must have ended with brāhmaṇai, not with brāhmaṇairā. 
--><!-- 
L26. SK read sadaṇḍa (in cpd), but the anusvāra is clear. 
--></p>
